2 Occupation and Sleep duration

With different occupations being faced with different challenges in not only life but in profession their sleep is bound to be affected. Within this graph we are able to view how the averages change based off the occupation. With the graph and the table we are able to see how the sleep duration ranges from 5.8 hours as the min and 8.5 hours as the max. Along within this visualization were able to see how engineers have the highest average sleep while sale represenatives show the lowest average sleep.

library(janitor)

#Average Sleep Duration per Occupation Table 
avgSleepDuration <- data %>%
  group_by(Occupation)%>%
  summarize(avgSleepDuration = mean(SleepDuration))

#Average Sleep Duration for Each Occupation
ggplot(avgSleepDuration) +
  aes(x = Occupation, y = avgSleepDuration, fill = Occupation) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c(Accountant = "#440154",
               Doctor = "#CEA2FD",
               Engineer = "#960019",
               Lawyer = "#0075EF",
               Manager = "#027091",
               Nurse = "#5DCFCA",
               `Sales Representative` = "#27A833",
               Salesperson = "#097A30",
               Scientist = "#FF9913",
               `Software Engineer` = "#3F4D03",
               Teacher = "#8A3324")
  ) +
  labs(x = "Occupation",
       y = "Average Sleep Duration (hours)",
       title = "Average Sleep Duration for Each Occupation",
       fill = "Occupation"
       )+
  coord_flip() +
  theme_classic()+
  theme_bw(base_size = 16)

4 Statics

These metrics provide a comprehensive overview of variability, central tendency, and outliers within our study population, informing research on sleep health and potential interventions. Analyzing these statistics aids in identifying risk factors associated with inadequate or excessive sleep duration and contributes to our understanding of sleeps impact on overall well-being. Using this were able to show that some testers arent reaching the necessary amount of sleep within Q1-Q3. Showing that testers only were able to reach the recommended amount of sleep within Q4.

sleepDurStats <- data%>%
  select(SleepDuration) %>%
  summarize(
    Min = min(data$SleepDuration, na.rm = TRUE),
    Q1 = quantile(data$SleepDuration, probs = 0.25, na.rm = TRUE),
    Median = median(data$SleepDuration, na.rm = TRUE),
    Q3 = quantile(data$SleepDuration, probs = 0.75, na.rm = TRUE),
    Q4 = quantile(data$SleepDuration, probs = 1, na.rm = TRUE),
    Max = max(data$SleepDuration, na.rm = TRUE),
    Mean = mean(data$SleepDuration, na.rm = TRUE),
    SD = sd(data$SleepDuration, na.rm = TRUE)
  )%>%
  round(., 2)

#Polished Sleep Duration Descr. Stats Table
# sleepDurKable <- sleepDurStats %>%
sleepDurStats %>%
  kable(
    caption = "Sleep Duration Descriptive Statistics",
    booktabs = TRUE,
    align = c("c",rep("c",6))
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(
    bootstrap_options = c("striped"),
    font_size = 16

5 SQL Statics

Using different packages like SQL were able to show both the frequency and the probability. The frequency shows us that most cases show have a sleep duration of 6 hours and also is proven in the probability as we calculated that is the most likely sleep duration. Along with 6.1 being the second most likely sleep duration. Which both are below the recommended amount from the CDC .

library(DBI)
library(RSQLite)

# Connect to an SQLite database
con <- dbConnect(RSQLite::SQLite(), "SleepHealth.db")

# Step 1: Read the CSV file
rawsleepdata <- read.csv("sleepdata.csv")

# Drop the existing "sleepdata" table if it exists
dbExecute(con, "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS sleepdata")
## [1] 0
# Write the data frame to the SQLite database
dbWriteTable(con, "sleepdata", rawsleepdata)

# Check if the table has been created in the database
dbListTables(con)
## [1] "sleepdata"
# Query to get frequency table
query <- "
  

SELECT 
    SleepDuration,
    COUNT(SleepDuration) AS frequency,
    COUNT(SleepDuration) * 1.0 / (SELECT COUNT(SleepDuration) FROM sleepdata) AS probability
  
    
FROM 
    sleepdata
GROUP BY 
    SleepDuration
ORDER BY 
    SleepDuration;


  

"
#Find the probabilty of someone having a sleep duration under 7 and then find the vice versa.

#Find the probability of someone with a good sleep quality having a high stress levels.

#Find the correlation percentage between stress and sleep duration vs sleep duration and sleep disorders 

# Execute the query
tryCatch({
  result <- dbGetQuery(con, query)
  head(result)
}, error = function(e) {
  print(paste("Error:", e$message))
})
